──────────────────────────────────────────────
26–30: FORMS, GET vs POST, INPUT FIELDS
──────────────────────────────────────────────

GET vs POST Methods in Forms
- Purpose: Transmit form data between client (browser) and server
- HTTP facilitates communication between browser and server

GET Method
- Requests data from a specified resource
- Name/value pairs from form fields sent in URL stream
- Example:
  <form action="send.php" method="get">
      First Name: <input type="text" name="fname">
      Last Name: <input type="text" name="lname">
  </form>
- Properties:
  * Requests can be cached
  * Remain in browser history
  * Should only retrieve data
  * Length restrictions
  * Cannot be used for sensitive data
  * Can be bookmarked

POST Method
- Submits data to be processed at a specified resource
- Name/value pairs sent in HTTP message body
- Example:
  <form action="send.php" method="post">
      First Name: <input type="text" name="fname">
      Last Name: <input type="text" name="lname">
  </form>
- Properties:
  * No data length restrictions
  * Cannot be bookmarked
  * Does not remain in browser history
  * Requests are never cached

Input Fields – Form Heading and Labels
- Form heading: Employment Application
- Row 2, column 1: First Name label
- Row 3, column 1: Last Name label

Text Input Field
- Syntax:
  <input type="text" name="fname" maxlength="50">
- Attributes:
  * name – used for PHP script processing
  * maxlength – limits input characters
- Notes:
  * Keep lowercase, simple, no special characters
  * Copy/paste for multiple fields (lname, etc.)

Select Menus (Dropdowns)
- Syntax:
  <select name="position">
      <option value="Ac">Accountant</option>
      <option value="Re">Receptionist</option>
      <option value="Ad">Administrator</option>
      <option value="Su">Supervisor</option>
  </select>
- Experience Level Example:
  <select name="experience">
      <option value="Entry">Entry Level</option>
      <option value="Very">Very Experienced</option>
  </select>

Checkboxes – Job Type
- Syntax:
  <input type="checkbox" name="ft"> Full Time
  <input type="checkbox" name="pt"> Part Time
  <input type="checkbox" name="ct"> Contract
- Notes:
  * Multiple selections allowed
  * Text next to checkbox for clarity

Radio Buttons – Employment Status
- Syntax:
  <input type="radio" name="estatus" value="Employed"> Employed
  <input type="radio" name="estatus" value="Unemployed"> Unemployed
  <input type="radio" name="estatus" value="Student"> Student
- Notes:
  * Only one selection allowed per group
  * All radio buttons share same name attribute

Text Area – Additional Comments
- Syntax:
  <textarea name="comments" cols="50" rows="5"></textarea>
- Notes:
  * Multi-line input
  * Scrollbars automatically appear

Submit and Reset Buttons
- Syntax:
  <input type="submit" name="submit" value="Submit">
  <input type="reset" name="reset" value="Reset">
- Notes:
  * Submit sends form data to PHP script specified in form action
  * Reset clears all input fields

Key Points – Forms
- GET: data in URL, bookmarkable, cached, length-limited
- POST: data in body, no length restriction, not cached, cannot bookmark
- Input fields: text, select, checkbox, radio, textarea
- Field names important for backend processing

──────────────────────────────────────────────
31–35: IFRAMES, TABLE LAYOUTS, HEADER, CALLOUT BAR, IMAGES
──────────────────────────────────────────────

Iframes
- Embed one HTML page inside another
- Syntax:
  <iframe src="https://www.ask.com" width="100%" height="400">
      Your browser does not support iframes.
  </iframe>
  <iframe src="https://www.bing.com" width="100%" height="400">
      Your browser does not support iframes.
  </iframe>
- Notes:
  * Useful for displaying multiple search engines or external content
  * Provide fallback text for unsupported browsers

Building Page Layout with Tables (No CSS)
- Tables used as layout containers
- Limitations: inline styles only
- Benefits: understand object placement, tabular data insertion, text formatting

Header Section
- Main table: width="100%", height="60px", border="0", cellspacing="5", cellpadding="5", bgcolor="#000000"
- Nested table: width="547px", border="0", align="center", cellpadding="1", cellspacing="1"
- Each link inside own <td>
- Example:
  <table width="100%" height="60" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" bgcolor="#000000">
    <tr>
      <td align="left">
        <table width="547" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1">
          <tr>
            <td width="96"><font face="Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif" color="#FFFFFF"><h3>Home</h3></font></td>
            <td width="...">...</td>
          </tr>
        </table>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>

Callout Bar (Website Name + Phone)
- Outer table: width="100%", height="150px", border="0", cellpadding="5", cellspacing="5", bgcolor="#D3D3D3"
- Nested table: width="708px", border="0", cellpadding="1", cellspacing="1"
- Two columns:
  1. Left: <strong>My Business</strong><br>Website
  2. Right: <strong>Call Us Today:</strong> 123-456-7890
- Example:
  <table width="100%" height="150" border="0" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="5" bgcolor="#D3D3D3">
    <tr>
      <td align="center">
        <table width="708" border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1">
          <tr>
            <td width="338" align="left"><font><strong>My Business</strong><br>Website</font></td>
            <td width="370" align="right"><font><strong>Call Us Today:</strong> 123-456-7890</font></td>
          </tr>
        </table>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>

Main Image Section
- Nested table under callout bar
- Syntax:
  <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
    <tr>
      <td align="center">
        <table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
          <tr>
            <td align="center">
              <img src="mainimage.jpg" width="800" height="400" alt="Main Image">
            </td>
          </tr>
        </table>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
- Notes:
  * Image in same folder as HTML
  * Center-aligned with <td align="center">

Key Notes
- Iframes embed external pages
- Tables for layout: header, callout, main image
- Nested tables for alignment
- Inline styles (CSS later)
- Practice object insertion, text formatting, forms, basic styling

